<subSubSection id="8634EBAF2EAD8910037E3E98A34539E7" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="40D1D9925275B96E8FE01D765FE89BFA" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B79C70BFD2A5807751037C9A0BE7F77" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
From the species name &quot; 
<emphasis id="3B68C60D638565258E1AE7161F27B21E" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">hova</emphasis>
&quot; with the Greek prefix &quot; 
<emphasis id="1C56E226BB4C19ACC518C997F6A021C1" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">para</emphasis>
&quot; meaning resembling 
<taxonomicName id="E098EA4470743176796DD22D2CD0C7B6" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="E256E5A55B748934498892ABB352DE55" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="95513D7E93DE4D9C9F8B62761B393E68" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="E15849DEA6862F72D361AA0429330DDD" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<pageBreakToken id="D02347EF24DA739379D7C30261694E03" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" start="start">Remarks</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B3B7297CD2BA1001FA7E8283A882936" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="37CDC97E32D7BDF91BA71A26D14939C5" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hova">
<emphasis id="325C5C03D801A7D6A8F23BA630E74AC8" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Orthogonalys hova</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and initially we considered the two males as large specimens of that species. However, the following differences justify its recognition as a distinct species: antenna with only about 4 central antennomeres completely white; clypeus white; genae almost completely white; posterior angles of pronotum white; mesoscutellum with anterior width about longer than medial length and with distinct median furrow in posterior half (
<figureCitation id="0EA32DC425B44BF09C90B10C54750A9C" captionStart="Figures 29–30" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figures 29 - 30. Orthogonalys parahova, holotype male. 29 Dorsolateral view. 30 Mesosoma and metasoma, dorsal view." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11365" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
); and paramere of male genitalia longer, about 1.8 times as long as broad and rounded at its apex (
<figureCitation id="0F0772B18C96F75191337C7C6F8CA1DA" captionStart="Figures 31–34" captionStartId="F10" captionText="Figures 31 - 34. Orthogonalys parahova, holotype male. 31 Head, front view. 32 Head, dorsal view. 33 Apex of abdomen and male genitalia, lateral view. 34, Mandibles." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/11366" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
). The parameres resemble the long, rounded parameres of 
<taxonomicName id="51F97942459AAC2C89A200A998EEF708" authorityName="Smith &amp; Tripotin" authorityYear="2012" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalidae" genus="Orthogonalys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="maculata">
<emphasis id="B2AA446655A85B703AE3A6D6C9553923" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Orthogonalys maculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
